name: Supplemental Learning Group: PSYCH-UA 30, Personality - [Duman's Section]
description:
Supplemental Learning Groups (SLGs) are lecture specific and give you a chance to practice and test your understanding of the material from the past week's lecture(s) in a collaborative group environment. This is process-based learning, meaning if you continue to attend, your learning will compound over the course of the semester. One time attendance will likely not be very helpful.

In order for this to be effective:

- You must come ready to collaborate.

- You must come ready to speak.

- You must be active.

This will be a framework that you might not be used to. In this space, the primary aim is to construct knowledge, which can feel frustrating.

name: Tandon Peer Justice Zone
description:
The Tandon Peer Justice Zone is a DEI initiative for Tandon students and led by Tandon students! Our Belonging Builders will lead you through the Justice Zone session, helping you to develop an understanding of frequently used concepts—such as diversity, equity, and social justice—through the lens of race and racism. Throughout this two-hour session, participants reflect on their own identities and challenge their daily practices to begin a journey toward critical consciousness. 
 
Snacks will be provided. Students can sign up for sessions here.

name: Race & Identity in the U.S. Workshop
description:
Our second  Identity and Inclusion for International Students workshop of the school year is here! In this session, Race and Identity in the US, we will unpack aspects of our identity through the lens of racial identity in the United States. We will explore the historical context of race and racism in the U.S. as well as learn key terms and vocabulary that will help you navigate conversations on race, identity, and diversity. How do these conversations differ in the U.S. compared to your home country? What is racism and what are some of the different ways it might present itself in the U.S.? How have your views on your own identity changed since arriving in the U.S.? 

 

This workshop will be a safe space to ask questions, engage in dialogue with one another, and unpack any assumptions you may have about U.S. identities. Lunch will be provided!

name: Movie and Cards Night!
description:
THE MOVIE

We will have a screening of the 50 minute documentary film Double Dummy, a bridge film that focuses on a U.S. junior team at the World Youth Team Championships in 2012. It’s IMdB summary reads: 

“To say that you played a hand double dummy is the highest compliment that you can pay a bridge player. It means to play the hand as if you know where all the cards are. This film is a celebration of the card game bridge. Through the lens of the 2012 World Youth Team Championships, the filmmakers show that bridge is not just a game for old people. It is a vibrant game played and loved by people of all ages and a great pastime.”

It received a 7.9 rating overall on IMbD, and honors the wonderful game many of us have been working on through an interesting youth perspective. With it’s under an hour runtime, and its explanations designed to be understandable for those not familiar with bridge, it makes a nice addition to a Saturday night and one’s overall bridge knowledge.

THE FOOD

We hope to never disappoint with our food selection, and for our movie screening, we went the extra mile to provide a full Movie Night snack experience. With popcorn popped throughout the night so it’s fresh whenever you arrive and an array of seasonings to choose from served in authentic theater-style popcorn holders, to tons of candy (with a great assortment of both chocolate and non-chocolate sweets), along with soda and water! 

THE GAMES

After (and during if you wish) the movie screening, there will be ample time to play some of our favorite card games, including bridge of course and finding friends. Grab a nametag, and join a table! No experience required, and if you’d like to try something new we would love to teach you! There will also be bridge documents available if you’d like to learn or review some concepts or get more context for the documentary’s subject game.

name: PSoc Dual-Specialist Periodontal Symposium
categories: ['Academic', 'Mentorship & Advising', 'Medical & Health Professions', 'Professional & Career Development', 'Education', 'Professional Networking', 'Leadership']
description:
RSVP TO EVENT HERE

The Dual-Specialist Periodontal Symposium is a unique and inspiring event that brings together leading periodontists who have chosen to expand their expertise by becoming dual-certified in another dental specialty. This symposium will provide attendees with a rare opportunity to gain insights from professionals who have taken their careers beyond the traditional boundaries of periodontics.

The symposium will feature a series of concise 20-25 minute presentations by dual-specialist periodontists who are also certified in endodontics, orthodontics, prosthodontics, dental anesthesiology, oral medicine, business administration, dental public health, and organized dentistry. Each speaker will share their personal journey, explaining how and why they chose to pursue dual certification, and how their additional expertise has shaped their approach to patient care, research, and professional growth. Guest speakers may also choose to include clinical cases in their presentations and a short Q&A will conclude the event. 

The event aims to:

  • Promote Professional Growth: By exposing attendees to the diverse career paths within periodontics, the symposium seeks to inspire students to explore the full spectrum of opportunities available in the field.
  • Foster Education & Collaboration: The symposium will encourage interdisciplinary learning and collaboration, highlighting how dual-specialization can enhance patient outcomes and broaden the scope of dental practice.
  • Build a Supportive Community: The event will serve as a platform for future periodontists to connect with mentors and peers, fostering a supportive environment that encourages professional development and lifelong learning.

Perks: 

  • Complimentary breakfast food & beverage included in the event price
  • Network with leading professionals, peers, and potential mentors in a supportive community
  • Exposure to diverse career paths & opportunities through unique insights of dual-specialist periodontists 
  • Explore clinical cases presented by guest speakers

Speaker Line-Up: (*Subject to Change)

  1. Perio-Prosth: Dr. Zahra Bagheri - PENDING
  2. Perio-Ortho: PENDING
  3. Perio-Endo: Dr. Mike Sabeti
  4. Perio-Anesthesiology: Dr. Charles Neidorff
  5. Perio-Oral Medicine: Dr. Michael Bral
  6. Perio-MBA: Dr. Carlo Ercoli
  7. Perio-MPH: Dr. Stephanie Russell

Affordable Registration Fees:

FREE: NYUCD Residents & Faculty
"Early Bird" Discount (until Oct 14th): 
$7 - NYU DDS Students 
$12 NYU Pre-Dental & Students from other institutions
Standard Fee (after Oct. 14th):
$9 - NYU DDS Students 
$15 NYU Pre-Dental & Students from other institutions
 
PAYMENT INSTRUCTIONS:
1. Visit: https://web.dental.nyu.edu/events/clubs/
2. Enter: CLUB: PERIODONTAL CLUB; MEMO: PSOC SYMPOSIUM, [EARLY BIRD or STANDARD ticket], [NYU DDS or PRE-DENTAL or OTHER]
- For example, "psoc symposium, early bird, nyu dds"
3. Complete the google form (at the top of this page).

Fundamentally, the Dual-Specialist Periodontal Symposium is designed to empower attendees to envision and pursue dynamic and fulfilling careers in periodontics, enriched by the knowledge and skills gained through additional specialization. Contact nyucd.periosociety@gmail.com for additional information.

name: Urban Birding PT:2 (Fall 2024)
description:
FALL URBAN BIRDING pt.2

Date: October 19 11:00 - 2:00

Location: Meet at the lower playground (40.81028741967658, -73.95573572909927) in Morningside Park

Lead: Harlan (ecw9572@nyu.edu)+Rafael

 

Join us for a bird walk at Morningside park, one of the lesser explored parks but no less incredible! Come see sapsuckers, kinglets, and warblers - straggling migrants who will soon leave NYC for their winter homes. We will meet at 11. Location linked above. This small incredibly urban park is nestled in a part of Harlem with a rich history. Additonally it serves as a vital refuge for the native bird species living at the heart of the concrete jungle, and also as a critical stop over spot for a variety of fall migrants.

name: NYU ETSA: Game Design with Louis Gaitan
description:
Join Our 6-Session Unity Game Design Workshop!

Are you ready to dive into the world of game design? This fall, embark on a creative journey with our hands-on Unity workshop series, led by seasoned game developer Luis. Over the course of six sessions in September and November, Luis will teach you the essentials of game design and prototyping using Unity, one of the industry's leading platforms.

In each session, you'll learn step-by-step how to turn your ideas into interactive, playable games — all with just your laptop. From beginner basics to advanced techniques, this workshop is perfect for both newcomers and those wanting to expand their skill set.

What You'll Need:

  • Your laptop with Unity and Visual Studio pre-installed (download them before the first session using this link)
  • Game ideas and a passion for creating!

Don’t miss this opportunity to learn from a pro and connect with fellow game enthusiasts. A more detailed tutorial will be provided after registration to help you get started.

Spaces are limited, so sign up today and start building your dream game!

name: Supplemental Learning Group - MATH-UA 9, ATF - [Stine Lecture ONLY]
description:
Supplemental Learning Groups (SLGs) are lecture specific and give you a chance to practice and test your understanding of the material from the past week's lecture(s) in a collaborative group environment.

This is process-based learning, meaning if you continue to attend, your learning will compound over the course of the semester.

One time attendance will likely not be very helpful.

In order for this to be effective:

- You must come ready to collaborate.

- You must come ready to speak.

- You must be active.

This will be a framework that you might not be used to. In this space, the primary aim is to construct knowledge, which can feel frustrating.

name: Procrastination Power Hour – Sunday Session
description:
Think of a Procrastination Power Hour as a structured study session designed to streamline productivity and hold you accountable to get your homework done!

Procrastination Power Hours are designed to help students fight procrastination and get their homework done efficiently, both in the short and long-term. This program aims to help students establish a productive homework routine by leveraging social support, imposing a consistent structure and routine on study time, and using external rewards as motivation to build consistent habits.

This program works best if you attend every week, but you are welcome to register any time throughout the semester.

name: NYU RADical Health | Building Resilience
categories: ['Health & Wellness', 'Professional & Career Development', 'Community', 'Find Your People', 'Navigate NYU', 'Invest in Academic & Personal Growth', 'Prioritize Wellbeing & Safety', 'Dialogue & Difference']
description:
Want to strengthen your mindfulness and connect with other NYU students? RADical Health is the perfect place for you.

 

RADical health provides students with an opportunity to hear esteemed guest speakers touch on topics related to student wellbeing and discuss how they can implement their advice into their own lives. In addition, by attending all 4 topics of offered RADical Health sessions, students will have the opportunity to get a “Career Accelerator” certification through the NYU Wasserman Center for Career Development to add to their resume and LinkedIn page. Additionally, they will unlock a VIP museum hack experience! Register your specific lab here.

 

Building Resilience touches on self-care, stress management, understanding stress cycles, and centers around the question of “why am I stressed?”

 

Free snacks will be provided - join us for a lovely time and even more beautiful conversations!

name: Global Awards for the Environment: Hollings
description:
The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) Hollings Scholarship is awarded annually to students seeking careers in oceanic and atmospheric science, research, technology and education. The scholarship provides two years of academic year tuition assistance, a summer internship, and funding to attend a conference.

Eligibility: Open to current sophomores with a declared major in a discipline including, but not limited to, oceanic, environmental, biological, and atmospheric sciences, mathematics, engineering, remote sensing technology, physical and social sciences including geography, physics, hydrology, geomatics, or teacher education that support NOAA's programs and mission. Related discipline areas of study may include biological, social, and physical sciences; mathematics; engineering; computer and information sciences; and science teacher education. Minimum GPA of 3.0. U.S. Citizens.

Can't make this session? Please still RSVP! This session will be recorded, and the recording will be shared with everyone who RSVPs.

Note on Accessibility: New York University and the NYU Office of Global Awards provide reasonable accommodations to students with disabilities. For any questions or to notify us of additional accommodation requests, please email the Office of Global Awards at globalawards@nyu.edu at least one week prior to the event.

name: Tandon Peer Justice Zone
description:
The Tandon Peer Justice Zone is a DEI initiative for Tandon students and led by Tandon students! Our Belonging Builders will lead you through the Justice Zone session, helping you to develop an understanding of frequently used concepts—such as diversity, equity, and social justice—through the lens of race and racism. Throughout this two-hour session, participants reflect on their own identities and challenge their daily practices to begin a journey toward critical consciousness. 
 
Snacks will be provided. Students can sign up for sessions here.
